  "reasoning": "Applied CEFR A1 descriptors to evaluate vocabulary level-appropriateness and communicative function classification. Themes were identified by topic shifts in the conversation, and vocabulary was split into active (student-produced) and passive (teacher-introduced, student understood). Communicative functions follow the CEFR functional categories: describing, narrating, explaining, requesting information. The pedagogical arc shows a well-structured lesson moving from activation to input to controlled practice to freer practice, consistent with a PPP (Presentation-Practice-Production) approach.",
  "lesson_arc": "The lesson follows a classic PPP structure. It opens with a warm-up conversation about Lukas's work week (activation of prior knowledge, surfacing of errors for the lesson topic). The teacher uses Lukas's natural error (\"I go with the car\") as a bridge into the planned topic: transport and directions. The presentation phase introduces transport vocabulary, verb collocations (take/drive/ride/walk), and the \"go by\" structure. Controlled practice follows with tense drills (present/past/future transport sentences). The lesson then transitions to directions vocabulary (position words, landmarks) and progresses through increasingly free practice: repeating directions, giving directions from a map, and finally a phone role-play giving directions to a colleague. The review phase consolidates with a correct/incorrect exercise and a summary of key error patterns. Homework is assigned for continued practice.",
